In popular culture[edit]

In the 1960s, Mattel released a series of American Airlines Stewardess Barbie dolls.[96]
Throughout the 1990s, American Airlines was featured in John Hughes' Home Alone trilogy of movies.[97][98][99]
In August 2008, in a Season 2 episode of Mad Men (Episode 2, titled "Flight 1"), Pete Campbell's father is a passenger on American Airlines Flight 1 which crashes shortly after takeoff from Idlewild Airport (now John F. Kennedy International Airport), killing all the passengers and crew on board.
American Airlines was a sponsor of a travelogue segment of the Univision show Sábado Gigante titled La Cámara Viajera.
American Airlines was extensively featured in the 2009 movie Up in the Air as part of a marketing tie-in between the airline and Paramount Pictures.[100]
In 2013, American Airlines collaborated with Disney to promote Planes by featuring a cameo appearance of a passenger airliner named Tripp, with the new American Airlines livery to promote its new image.[101]
Airport 1975 used a Boeing 747-123 Freighter (cargo variant) s/n 20390 (registration N9675), leased from American Airlines.[102]

